Irish President Refers to Development of Relations between DPRK and EU 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- Ireland, which chairs the European Union, will contribute to the development of the relations between the DPRK and the EU.
Irish President Mary Mcaleese said this when receiving credentials from new DPRK Ambassador e. p. to the country Ri Yong Ho on Feb. 27. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The president hoped that the Korean people would overcome the temporary difficulties in their economic field and achieve prosperity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Saying that the two countries have had many things in common historically, he hoped that visits and exchange between the two countries would become brisk in accordance with the diplomatic relations that exist between them.

Japan's Adoption of Amendment to Law Denounced in Ukraine 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- The Central Committee of the Lenin Communist Youth Union of Ukraine released a statement on Feb. 24 denouncing Japan for adopting an "amendment to the law on foreign exchange".
 The statement noted that the adoption of the amendment is a wanton violation of international law, adding that this once again proves that the Japanese authorities are totally subject to the U.S. administration desperately working to stifle the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's adoption of the amendment diametrically runs counter to the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration and is aimed to deter the six-way talks from settling the nuclear issue between the DPRK and the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It indicates what a dangerous phase the imperialists' moves against the world people have reached and once again underscores the need the world people to form a worldwide anti-imperialist front to cope with such moves. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We express solidarity with the Korean people in their efforts for independent development.

Koreans Called Upon to Pave Wide Avenue for Independent Reunification 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- All the Koreans in the north, the south and abroad should pave a wide avenue for independent national reunification through national cooperation against outsiders, fully convinced of and optimistic about sure victory, says Rodong Sinmun today in a signed article dedicated to the 85th anniversary of the March 1 Popular Uprising.
 The article says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The uprising was participated in by a great number of patriotic youth and students reared by Kim Hyong Jik, an outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea, and other people of all social standings. It was a patriotic uprising as it fully demonstrated the Korean people's staunch spirit of struggling for independence against outsiders and dealt a telling blow at the Japanese imperialist colonial rulers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Nearly a century has passed since the uprising. This is a glorious history of the struggle for independence against foreign forces as the Koreans have waged a strenuous struggle to put an end to the outsiders' domination and their moves for aggression and build new Korea, reunified and free. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 President Kim Il Sung is a peerless patriot as he embarked upon the road to save the nation's destiny in order to realize the nation's strong desire for sovereignty and independence and performed immortal exploits in the history of the nation through tireless energetic leadership and great devotion. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The cause of national independence pioneered by Kim Il Sung is being inherited and carried out by leader Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The present generation has an urgent task to fulfill for the nation. They should put a definite end to the outsiders' aggression and interference and accomplish the cause of independent reunification, carrying forward the history and tradition of struggle for independence against outsiders. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean nation's struggle for independence against outsiders is a nationwide patriotic struggle against the U.S. and Japan to resolutely smash the U.S. and Japanese aggression forces' moves to isolate and stifle the DPRK and pave a wide avenue for national reunification with high national self-respect, awareness of independence and the might of the concerted efforts of the Koreans. All the Koreans should turn out as one in a just and patriotic struggle to frustrate the U.S. and Japanese aggression forces' reckless moves to invade Korea in a do-or-die spirit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They should renew their strong will for independence against outsiders to reject and oppose outsiders keen on aggression and protect the dignity and the sovereignty of the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They should build a structure of the Korean nation's confrontation with the U.S. through practical actions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the Koreans should form a front of a powerful common struggle against the U.S. in denouncing its moves to interfere in the internal affairs of the Korean nation and launch a military aggression against the DPRK. They should wage a dynamic anti-U.S. and anti-war struggle, true to the Songun politics, proud of being protected by the politics praised by the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They should give a strong impetus to the process of reconciliation and the cause of reunification under the banner of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
ï¿½@The victory in the struggle for independence against outsiders hinges upon all the Koreans' full play to the Korean nation-first spirit.

Withdrawal of Amended "Law on Foreign Exchange" Urged in Japan 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- The Japanese Women's Society for Solidarity with the Korean Women and the Japanese Women's Council on Feb. 5 sent a request to the prime minister, political parties and Diet men demanding the withdrawal of  the "amendment to the law on foreign exchange" which had been railroaded through the lower house.
 The request expressed deep concern over the passage of the amendment and disclosed its injustice and aggressive nature. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We think the revised law runs counter to the Japan-DPRK Pyongyang Declaration and it will only foster confrontation, the request said, and went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The government appears to contend that "the adoption of a law is one thing and its enforcement is another." But the practice of flouting law and brandishing sanctions cannot get the understanding and trust of the broad international community. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Moreover, we Japanese feel real pang and resentment at the fact that "bills" designed to rob the Koreans in Japan, victims to Japan's colonial rule, of their basic rights are under preparation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We think the government should revive the spirit of the Japan-DPRK Pyongyang Declaration and come out for dialogue and negotiation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We strongly urge the government to retract the amended "law on foreign exchange", seek a solution to the issue through frank dialogue and sincere negotiation, strive to set up new relationship between the two countries and help toward peace and stability in Northeast Asia.

Russian Artistes Perform for Guests of Honor 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- The visiting State Academy Ensemble of the Ministry of Interior of Russia Sunday gave a performance for guests of honor at the April 25 House of Culture.
 Appreciating the performance were Kim Ki Nam, secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea, Ji Jae Ryong, vice department director of the C.C., the WPK, Lieutenant General of the Korean People's Army Han Tong Gun and other Korean officials concerned, Russian Ambassador to the DPRK Andrei Karlov and staff members of the Russian embassy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The performance began with a chorus of the immortal revolutionary song of praise "Song of General Kim Il Sung" to the accompaniment of orchestral music. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The performers vigorously sang wartime songs such as "Battle of Justice" and "Forward" well depicting the features of the Russian soldiers and people who fought bravely in defense of their motherland in the patriotic war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In "Dance of Victory", "Market of Russia" and other dances they vividly depicted the national sentiments and optimistic life of the Russian people with diverse rhythms and highly refined artistry. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The performers put on the stage Korean songs including "Song of Sea" and "My Blessed Life" and songs and dances of different nations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 When "Song of General Kim Jong Il", the immortal revolutionary song of praise, reverberated through the auditorium, the audience loudly sang in chorus with the performers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A floral basket was presented to the performers in congratulation of the successful performance. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The performance continues.

Bikini Disaster Should Not Be Repeated 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- It is 50 years after a nuclear disaster took place on Bikini Island.
 The U.S. imperialists' H-bomb test on the island on March 1, 1954 inflicted a disaster upon islanders and fishermen of Japan's "Fukuryu Maru No.5" who were fishing near the island. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jin Bom, chairman of the Korean Anti-Nuke Peace Committee, told KCNA that the test of the U.S. imperialists, who dropped two nuclear bombs on Japan in August 1945, was another nuclear crime. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is an unanimous desire of humankind to live in a peaceful world free from nuclear weapons and war, he said. Nevertheless, the United States is trying hard to dominate the whole world, prompted by a nuclear strategy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The United States has become all the more outspoken in revealing its plan to launch a nuclear preemptive attack on those nations that  are standing in the way of the execution of its strategy for world supremacy and are out of favor with it, and non-nuclear weapon states, he said, and continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Bush administration, after designating the Democratic People's Republic of Korea as part of the "axis of evil" and a target of its nuclear preemptive attack, has published ahead with the development of small nuclear bombs for the purpose of destroying the DPRK's underground targets. The United States has already deployed weapons of mass destruction including some 1,000 nuclear weapons in south Korea to attack the DPRK. Not content with them, however, it has brought to south Korea sophisticated weapons tested in the Afghan and Iraqi wars of aggression. The fact indicates that the U.S. intention to start the second war of aggression, a nuclear war, on the Korean peninsula at any cost has already begun to be translated into practice. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 But if a war breaks out in Korea, it will not be confined only to the peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Bikini disaster should not be repeated. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean Anti-Nuke Peace Committee, together with such organizations in the world, will fight staunchly to prevent a nuclear disaster.

Voices of Indignation at Japanese Imperialism Still Reverberate in Korea
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- Eighty-five years have passed since the entire Korean people turned out in the March First Popular Uprising against the colonial rule of the Japanese imperialist aggressors.
 The uprising was an eruption of the pent-up anger and resentment of the Korean people who had been exposed to extreme humiliation and mistreatment under the brutal colonial rule of the Japanese imperialists since they occupied Korea by force of arms. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese imperialists changed their "Residence-General" into "Korean Government-General" in 1910 in order to further intensify their colonial rule over Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They set up more than 16,200 gendarme and police machineries, 20-odd prisons and temporary jails in different parts of the country to arrest, &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
imprison and massacre Koreans at random.  Terauchi, the first "governor-general", raved that Koreans should obey to Japanese law or die and drove the military and police to the harsh repression of the Korean people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In Pyongyang, thousands of citizens including young people and students gathered in the playground of Sungdok Women's School at twelve noon on March 1 when a bell was telling time. There they solemnly declared Korea was an independent state and staged a demonstration, shouting the slogans "Long live the independence of Korea!" and "Japanese and their troops, get out of Korea!" The number of demonstrators reached more than 100,000 in a short time. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In Seoul, too, there was a demonstration involving hundreds of thousands of people. Among them were peasants who came to Seoul from different parts of the country to see the funeral service of King Kojong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The uprising developed into a nation-wide resistance, spreading from Pyongyang and Seoul to all the 13 provinces of the country and other countries including the northeastern areas and Shanghai of China, the Far East region of Russia and Hawaii. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese imperialists mobilized mounted police and troops to cold-bloodedly massacre over 100,000 demonstrators by showering bullets on them or sabring them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  The cheers of the uprisers are still reverberating in the country, giving rise to national indignation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean people will surely make Japan pay for all the crimes committed by the Japanese imperialists and for the blood shed by the uprisers.

Declaration on National Independence Issued
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 1 (KCNA) -- The National Reconciliation Council, the Korean Council of Religionists and the south side's headquarters for the promotion of functions common to the nation jointly issued a March 1 declaration on national independence on Monday on the occasion of the 85th anniversary of the March 1 Popular Uprising.
 The March 1 Popular Uprising demonstrated the spirit of independence of the Koreans determined to reject the Japanese imperialists' rule and stand on their own feet. It manifested the self-esteem and stamina of the Koreans who had defended the sovereignty and dignity for thousands of years, the declaration said, and continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This year all the Koreans in the north and the south and abroad should strive to avert the threat of a war posed by outsiders and pave a wide avenue for peace and reunification by their concerted efforts and further strengthen the unity of all the Koreans in the north and the south and overseas. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They should resolutely counter Japan's distortion of history and its militarist attempt with the strength of the whole nation and pool their efforts to implement the June 15 joint declaration this year, too, regarding it as a landmark for reunification.
